# route table priority

1 different prefix
  The order in the table doesn't matter; routes with a longer prefix always take priority. 
  e.g. 123.x.x.128/27 and 123.x.x.151/32, 
  and the latter – more specific – route will take priority over the former (more generic one).

2 if two interfaces have the same destination, netmask, and gateway of 0.0.0.0,
  the first one will grab all the traffic for that network.

# clean route

while /bin/route del default gw 0.0.0.0 dev eth0;  do :; done
while /bin/route del default gw 0.0.0.0 dev wlan0; do :; done

# route 
  双网卡单点转发：route add  192.168.2.49 gw 192.168.1.24

  num(route) = num(NIC) + num(IP)
  内核自动加路由：ifconfig eth0:0 192.168.3.49 
  Destination  Gateway   Genmask        Flags Metric Ref  Use Iface
  192.168.3.0  *         255.255.255.0  U     0      0      0 wlan0

# Linux[del时netmask必选]

    route del -net 192.168.2.0  gw 0.0.0.0  netmask 255.255.255.0 [dev eth0]
    route add -net 192.168.2.0  gw 0.0.0.0  netmask 255.255.255.0 [dev eth0]

            route add default gw 192.168.2.1
    busybox route add default gw xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx
    busybox route del default gw xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx

# win7
  net: 
  route -p add 10.41.0.0 mask 255.255.0.0 10.27.0.1
                      ^                    ^
                      destination          next hop(getway)

  host:
  route -p add 192.168.1.25 mask 255.255.255.255 192.168.1.24
        ^        ^                                ^
   persitent    destination                    next hop(getway)

  del:
  route 192.168.1.0
                  ^
                  网段
